The XRD pattern of GQDs@AgNPs (Fig. 10
                        ) indicates a peak at 2θ = 23.2° having Miller indices (002), which reflect that the GQDs present in the nanohybrid structure [21]. The inter-layer separation (
                           d
                        ) calculated comes out to be 0.39 nm, which is greater than pristine graphite (d = 0.34 nm) but smaller than that of GO (d = 0.88 nm) (Table S1 of SI). The behaviour of GQDs is attributed to the increase/decrease in the number of functional groups attached to its surface compared to graphite and GO. Besides, the peaks which appeared at 2θ = 38.7°, 44°, 65.3° and 77.6° are the characteristic peaks (JCPDS card No. 04–0783) of Ag having diffraction planes (111), (200), (220) and (311) and evidences the face-centered cubic (fcc) structure of AgNPs, as shown in Fig. S5 of SI [27,57]. Thus, these peaks indicate that both GQDs and pure crystalline AgNPs are present in the hybrid structure. Fig. 11
                         (a,b) shows the TEM images of GQDs@AgNPs nanohybrid, which further confirmed the formation of nearly spherical silver nanoparticles. The HR-TEM image (Fig. 11b) indicates how the GQDs get attached to AgNPs while reducing the Ag+ ions into AgNPs.
